<DOCNO> AP901231-0002 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
winning the olympics alone would have given 
atlanta reason to crow this year but then the heavyweight 
championship and what about landing a super bowl and a spot on 
the most liveable list and now grits meets glitz jane 
fonda too 
this citys triumphs finally gave substance to its boosters old 
nickname in 1990 it was hotlanta indeed 
true the olympics fireworks burst over a city that would pass a 
curfew to save its children from drug dealers true the mayor had 
to challenge preliminary census figures indicating his city was 
losing people 
but even if the ticker tape snowed on a cooling economy and on 
troubles common to urban area atlanta celebrated as it hadnt 
since the curtain went up on gone with the wind half a century 
ago 
in september a few months after being picked as the site of pro 
footballs 1994 super bowl dark horse atlanta beat out athens 
greece as host for the 1996 summer olympic games the confetti was 
barely swept up when hometowner evander holyfield brought boxings 
heavyweight title to the city tagged losersville for its sorry 
teams 
billboards around the nations 13th largest metropolitan area 
saluted hard work and chutzpah headlines hollered its 
atlanta on sidewalks and in grocery lines natives beamed 
at the atlanta historical society executive director john ott 
didnt know of another time when two parades had streamed down 
peachtree street within six weeks 
it may make atlantans like texans you know were the best 
were the greatest were the biggest he said we do have the 
sense that we have the wherewithal to capture things 
a city of dreams proclaimed atlanta magazine profiling 
its own parade of locals who realized grand visions from martin 
luther king jr to ted turner 
the latters atlantabased cable news network which many credit 
with raising the citys profile marked its 10th anniversary in 
1990 and in december ted and jane fonda that is whose causes 
and caresses filled the daily people columns announced their 
engagement 
along the way there were high marks for atlanta from arbiters 
as different as the population crisis committee tied for second 
highest score on list of worlds most liveable cities and the 
fortune industrial survey first among executives likely picks for 
future plant sites 
only three us cities attract more conventioneers and 
atlantas high profile this year will only enhance that said john 
jackson vice president of the atlanta convention and visitors 
bureau 
a few years ago i was in london and a gentleman told me we 
needed to get our boardwalks fixed people associated atlanta with 
atlantic city jackson said thats not going to happen 
anymore atlanta is on the world map 
the 1988 democratic national convention provided a smallerscale 
dress rehearsal for events the city is now committed to staging he 
said adding that atlanta managed the attention well then some 
15000 reporters descended on the city and 95 percent or more of 
the stories were positive 
in 1989 however atlanta led the nations large cities in 
serious crime according to fbi statistics even though the city 
has shed that dubious distinction as crime figures declined this 
year some reporters continue to cite it said angelo fuster press 
secretary for mayor maynard jackson its terribly frustrating 
he said 
in november the city council restored a curfew for children 16 
and under that hadnt been in effect in nearly a decade prompted 
earlier by the socalled atlanta child murders cases in 
calling for a new curfew a sponsor cited killings in her district 
including that of a 4yearold girl 
civil libertarians doubted the curfew was constitutional but 
the mayor said it would help us fight drugs and protect our 
children 
city hall damage controllers went to work after preliminary 
figures from the us census bureau said atlantas population fell 
from 425000 to 384000 between 1980 and 1990 the city contending 
it had grown to 437000 said census takers overlooked many and 
undercounted others it demanded a recount 
cracks even began to show in the smiling facade of unanimity 
that helped win the olympics residents near the proposed sites of 
certain venues protested that their neighborhoods would suffer 
some activists worried that officials would try to sweep 
lingering problems like homelessness from visitors view rather 
than working to solve them 
there are blighted neighborhoods in the path of stadiums all 
over atlanta that are going to have to be gentrified complained 
anita beaty director of the ctys task force for the homeless 
which counted 47000 individuals who sought emergency housing last 
year 
ms beaty said shes concerned that money which could go toward 
shelter and other needs will instead be used for superficial 
beautification she called for more public involvement in planning 
im no longer saying we dont want the olympics thats 
useless she said im saying how can we benefit how can 
we manage the impact 
the super bowl and the olympics are new chapters in an old story 
of selfpromotion and courting outsiders that has helped define the 
city that grew from a railroad terminus torched by gen william t 
sherman in the civil war atlanta adopted the motto resurgens 
latin for rising again and never forgot that goal 
after the civil war atlanta editor and orator henry grady 
trumpeted a new south less splendid on the surface but 
stronger at the core a hundred farms for every plantation and 
a diversified industry that meets the needs of this complex age 
northerners liked what they heard and yankee investment poured 
in to the new souths capital 
that typifies atlantas style welcome anybody particularly 
if theyve got a few dollars said jack spalding former editor 
of the atlanta journal 
people say the olympics good god how can you handle it 
spalding said but he cited precedents notably a civic showcase 
mounted just three decades after shermans destruction the 1895 
cotton states and international exposition it attracted 800000 
people nearly 10 times the citys population 
other than to get attention there was absolutely no 
justification for it spalding said a smile wrinkling his eyes 
atlantas always had a lot of imagination 
 
editors note christopher sullivan is the aps southeast 
regional reporter based in atlanta 
</TEXT>
