<TEXT>
in 1968 college student dan blue wanted to 
leave the farm and become a scientist but the assassinations of 
martin luther king jr and robert kennedy sent him in a new 
direction 
next month he is in line to become north carolinas first black 
house speaker 
blue was nominated unanimously dec 7 by democrats for the key 
legislative post his nomination followed the defeat of another 
black democrat former charlotte mayor harvey gantt in a bitter 
and racially divisive us senate campaign against jesse helms 
blue says the two events were not linked even before the 
election he already had commitments from house colleagues to vote 
for him the fact that they belived they could do so without 
backlash from constituents is saying a tremendous amount about 
north carolina i believe 
because democrats control 81 of the 120 seats in the house blue 
is virtually assured election when the general assembly convenes 
jan 30 blue 41 would be the first black speaker of the house in 
north carolina and the nations fourth assuming history didnt 
lose track of any during reconstruction 
blue won his first term in the state house in 1980 he has 
served as chairman of the legislative black caucus and sponsored 
the law declaring kings birthday a state holiday 
he was active in the jesse jackson and michael dukakis campaigns 
in 1988 blue also was instrumental in changing the states 
election laws last year to require 40 percent of the votes to win a 
primary rather than a 50 percent threshold that had been a barrier 
to black candidates 
blue grew up on a family farm in robeson county where the 
population is divided almost evenly among blacks whites and 
indians despite the 1954 us supreme court decision outlawing 
school segregation blue was bused across the county to a black 
school 
he arrived at predominantly black north carolina central 
university in durham during the upheavals over civil rights and 
vietnam 
there were the meetings at various churches or just meeting 
houses where young black students and young white students got 
together he said you developed an activisttype attitude you 
simply couldnt be in durham back in the mid60s without it 
infecting you to some degree 
blue was attracted by the role lawyers played in the movement 
they had a direct understanding of the system knowing that 
they had an obligation to make it work to make the overall society 
better 
all of us followed martin luther king blue said i guess 
my decision to go to law school was firmly fixed after he was 
assassinated with the kingkennedy assassinations 
but first blue completed his degrees in math and chemistry 
because you dont quit once youve embarked on a course 
he had decided to become a scientist after television reports on 
the first satellite sputnik launched by the soviets in 1957 
i remember distinctly all the news stories with douglas 
edwards and all of those folk on sputnik and how we were really 
making a push for science and all of that he said i just had 
it fixed in my head from the time that i was in second or third 
grade that i was supposed to become a scientist of some sort 
after graduating from duke universitys law school blue went to 
work at a raleigh law firm that included terry sanford a 
democratic former governor who is now a us senator 
blues first foray into politics as an 11yearold was nailing 
up sanford campaign signs in 1960 
in 1991 the major issue facing the state house is a projected 
budget shortfall of more than 1 billion 
there are more challenges when there are tough issues youve 
got to face but the rewards are certainly much greater too 
blue said 
my thing is that we steer this state on a sound course so 
that we truly do become that progressive beacon that folk from off 
a distance say we are and that id like to believe we are he 
said 
</TEXT>
