<TEXT>
in the vast rolling countryside 
of the northern transvaal efforts to end apartheid have sown 
conflict between white farmers and millions of blacks who want 
land 
the government has promised that laws prohibiting blacks from 
owning property in most of the country will be scrapped next year 
instead of easing tension plans to repeal the land acts have 
illuminated the deep divisions between blacks and whites about 
south africas future 
historical injustices resulting from landgrabbing over three 
centuries cannot easily be rectified now the star newspaper said 
in an editorial 
under the land laws 87 percent of south africa is reserved for 
the 5 million whites most of it agricultural land owned by fewer 
than 50000 farmers 
the 30 million blacks can own property only in black townships 
around cities and in the 10 tribal homelands on the remaining and 
worst 13 percent of south africas land 
how to undo the disparity is a contentious issues for the 
government and such black opposition groups as the african national 
congress as they negotiate a new constitution that will give blacks 
political power 
to blacks reform means reversing decades of injustice when 
laws perpetuated the white expansion that drove them from the land 
of their ancestors 
most delegates to a recent anc workshop on land reform approved 
a statement saying the state should play the principal role in 
effecting a major redistribution of land 
many white farmers see land reform as a leftist plot to strip 
them of their godgiven heritage as the proper caretakers of the 
land 
we feel there is no way the blacks are going to go onto our 
land said bill ruthven a supporter of the proapartheid 
conservative party 
south africas land acts of 1913 and 1936 forced blacks with 
small farms to give them up and move to homelands or work for 
whites the anc and other antiapartheid groups say those who lost 
their land should get it back and large portions of the country 
should be turned over to blacks 
the existing inequitable distribution of land must end said 
joanne yawitch coordinator of the private national land committee 
in order to redress the apartheid legacy theres going to have 
to be a strong policy of affirmative action 
ms yawitch also is an administrator of the anc land commission 
a central recommendation of the anc workshop was a strong 
government role in redistributing land including a program of 
loans and grants available to people of all races 
president fw de klerks government has offered no formal land 
policy but said current title deeds of farmers and landowners 
are safe 
the south african development bank which provides government 
loans for homeland developmewnt has suggested turning over 5 
million acres of stateowned land to blacks it also recommends 
that about 1000 white farmers with heavy debts to the government 
land bank sell their land to blacks in exchange for debt 
writeoffs 
such proposals smack of socialism to ruthven and other white 
farmers 
most are afrikaners the descendents of dutch settlers who 
dominate the government they were raised on the doctrine that god 
chose them to live in south africa and farm the land 
afrikaner farmers generally believe de klerk has betrayed his 
people by seeking to share power with blacks some belong to 
extreme rightwing groups that have organized private armies and 
vowed to keep their land 
piet swart director of the allwhite south african agricultural 
union said i dont think we need any government agency going 
around and telling people to whom to sell and for how much 
it isnt only a question of changing land ownership you have 
to have the wealth and entrepreneurial skills i think change is 
going to come not only in agriculture its going to take time it 
must take time 
his organization contends market forces alone should determine 
who buys and sells property after the land acts are gone 
swart granted such a policy would maintain the status quo since 
few blacks would have the money to buy farmland 
johann hartman of the transvaal agriculture union the most 
conservative chapter of the national organization said the debate 
should focus on how best to use the land 
agricultural land should be utilized for maximum production 
to feed the people of the land and not for political purposes he 
said 
ruthven a burly bearded man of 53 fears the government or 
independent agencies will provide loans or grants for blacks to buy 
land he also opposes affirmative action programs intended to help 
blacks become farmers 
for 300 years the white people have been doing this for 
blacks he said now were weaning them were not 
breastfeeding them anymore my nipples are sore 
