<TEXT>
whether you were pleased or peeved by the 
performance of americas legislature last year get ready for 
congressthe sequel 
the cast being sworn in this week for the 102nd congress is much 
as it was in the 101st but the unaddressed problems have grown to 
the point where those in starring roles must put in much bigger 
performances 
thomas s foley dwash returns as speaker of the house 
george mitchell dmaine as senate majority leader and robert h 
michel rill and bob dole rkan as minority leaders of the 
house and senate respectively 
their backups standins and bit players remain the same too 
as another twoyear period of governing begins thursday the 
football redskins a more popular washington institution make more 
roster changes than the voters make with congress 
the plot for the coming session picks up where things left off 
last fall but now its clear theres much more riding on every 
twist 
shooting has not broken out in the persian gulf but the level 
of tension has risen dramatically 
congress immediately faces the prospect of the jan 15 deadline 
by which iraqs saddam hussein is supposed to withdraw from kuwait 
in the event that president bush carries through with his threat 
to attack congress must decide whether to insist that he obtain a 
declaration of war or some other endorsement of the action 
the democrats in congress have so far been walking a fine line 
balancing their prerogatives under the constitution with the need 
to voice support for the presidents policy 
they also are keenly aware that in the aftermath of vietnam you 
can oppose a war but youd better not be seen as less than fully 
supporting american fighting men and women 
if bush fights a war and quickly wins democrats dont want to 
be seen as losers but if the gulf situation drags on in war or 
peace and becomes politically unpopular the democrats want to be 
able to sever their ties with him 
that will be a major theme at least for the first weeks of 
congress return 
i think its makeorbreak time for george bush dole said 
sunday on nbcs meet the press 
but the senate gop leader wasnt referring just to the persian 
gulf 
weve got twin problems i think he could do very well in 
the gulf and still go downhill on the economy dole said that 
may be more difficult to deal with in the final analysis than the 
gulf crisis 
like the gulf the issue of the economy was around when congress 
adjourned last october but it has become much more sharply defined 
since then as statistics show the recession looking deeper and 
perhaps lasting longer than believed a few months ago 
both congress and the white house will come under increasing 
pressure to address the nations economic problems but the huge 
federal deficit going up despite last falls approval of tax hikes 
and spending restraints might close the doors on many options 
the 101st congress was at times dominated by ethics debates and 
it looks as though the 102nd will be too 
the senate ethics committee this week resumes hearings on the 
keating five the senators who allegedly did improper favors for 
charles keating the top executive of a failed savings and loan 
institution 
will the five be punished by their peers and how many tens of 
billions of dollars of taxpayers money will be needed to continue 
the sampl bailout stay tuned 
related unfinished plot lines from the last congress include 
campaign reform and the congressional salary structure the 102nd 
congress begins with senators getting paid 101900 and house 
members 125100 will the senate follow the house and take a pay 
raise in exchange for limits on members outside earnings 
other issues returning from the last congress include bills to 
expand civil rights and to guarantee unpaid leave to workers after 
childbirth or for other family emergencies bush vetoed those 
measures 
congress also may attempt to address problems with health care 
insurance education and the nations trade imbalance 
its impossible to predict where events will carry the new 
congress but undoubtedly the players soon will be looking ahead to 
the ending the 1992 presidential and congressional elections 
 
editors note steven komarow covers congress for the associated 
press 
