chinese governments goal of doubling the gross national product in 
the coming decade 
i am fully confident in the realization of this goal yang 
said in new years greetings over radio beijing chinas staterun 
international radio 
senior leader deng xiaoping in 1978 set the goal of quadrupling 
chinas gnp by the turn of the century 
the gnp doubled during the booming 1980s and economists say that 
even with moderate growth chinas gnp should reach the goal of 
538 billion by the centurys end 
moderate growth is what the ruling communists mandated in the 
economic and social blueprint for the 1990s they released sunday 
the document suggests no dramatic new reform initiatives urging 
instead a return to basics 
economically that will mean more funds for agriculture raw 
materials industries the infrastructure and the military 
politically the emphasis will be on ideological discipline and 
collective labor 
for a long time to come we must persist in building the 
country through thrift and diligence the party central committee 
exhorted in the communique adopted at a secret sixday meeting 
that ended sunday 
the document filled the front pages today of all leading 
newspapers several newspapers also carried editorials applauding 
the party for the complete success of its meeting which had 
been delayed months by internal debates 
in the end the conservatives appeared to have dominated if 
only by sheer force of numbers in addition to 278 full and 
alternate members of the central committee the meeting was 
attended by 268 members of the central advisory commission and 
commission for discipline inspection party bodies made up largely 
of elderly ideological hardliners 
while leaving the door open to further marketstyle economic 
reforms the document stresses that the goal is to make the 
socialist system work better not replace it with capitalism 
the communique did not mention directly the collapse of 
socialism in most other countries but reflected the siege 
mentality that has developed among chinas aging revolutionaries 
since they crushed a democracy movement at home last year and 
watched similar movements succeed in eastern europe 
western observers believe the partys difficulty in drafting the 
plans for the 1990s reflects a leadership vaccuum senior leader 
deng 86 appears to have lost considerable prestige since the 
massive 1989 democracy movement and bloody crackdown that followed 
the communique made only a single perfunctory mention of dengs 
historical contributions it failed to mention his recent call for 
better more rapid and more effective reform 
reform was one of the key issues dividing the committee 
party elders such as 86yearold chen yun who helped implement 
initial marketstyle reforms in the 1980s argued that private 
enterprise and free markets should not be allowed to replace the 
state sector 
the communique echoed chens position by urging efforts to 
strengthen the inefficient debtridden state sector and establish 
more collective companies in the service sector now dominated by 
private entrepreneurs 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

