israels antiquities authority on monday 
dismissed a harvard scholar as chief editor of the dead sea 
scrolls citing health problems the professor recently created an 
uproar by making antijewish statements 
the editor britishborn divinity professor john strugnell was 
replaced by an israeli professor 
strugnell also had been criticized for the slow pace of 
publication of the leather scrolls discovered by a bedouin 
shepherd in 1946 in a cave near the dead sea 
the ancient manuscripts are among the most significant 
archaeological finds of the century because they include the oldest 
known texts of the old testmant and shed light on the origins of 
christianity and the history of judaism 
in his announcement monday amir drori the director of the 
israel antiquities authority said strugnell was being relieved at 
the suggestion of the agencys threeman scrolls advisory 
committee 
strugnell 60 and in ill health remains hospitalized in the 
united states associates said he could not be reached for 
comment 
he created a storm in israel following an interview published on 
nov 9 in the haaretz newspaper strugnell who is roman catholic 
described judaism as a racist religion just like hinduism 
in india 
asked what bothered him about judaism he said the fact that 
it survives it should have disappeared the solution to the 
jewish problem in my view is mass conversion to christianity and 
this is of course christian theology and not my dear option 
strugnell denied he was antijewish saying i dont love or 
hate jews more than i love or hate anybody else there are jews i 
cant stand and there are christians catholics even that i can 
stand even less 
he was severely criticized for the comments the weekly 
jerusalem report magazine headlined its article the jewhater who 
controls the scrolls and several editorials questioned whether a 
man with his opinions should continue as editor 
it was strugnells health problems that prompted an 
international editing team including professors frank cross of 
harvard and eugene ulrich of the university of notre dame to 
recommend earlier in december that strugnell be replaced 
the international team had recommended that he be replaced by 
three general editors but droris announcement named just one 
of the men israeli professor emanuel tov as the editor in chief 
the team also had recommended ulrich and father emile puech a 
french scholar working at the ecole biblique in jerusalem 
tov is the only israeli among the three a hebrew university 
professor he had been named as coeditor by the antiquities 
authority in october he is on sabbatical in the netherlands and 
could not be reached for comment 
a hebrew university scholar said on condition of anonymity that 
the change in editors means we are going to try and move things 
along with more speed 
he praised strugnell as a very fine scholar a very learned 
person but said that his personal problems had begun to 
interfere with the project 
strugnell has done research on the scrolls since 1952 and was 
editor since 1987 
magen broshi one of the members of the advisory committee 
estimated that about 80 percent of the scrolls have been published 
and that what remains is complicated because it requires piecing 
together thousands of fragments and interpreting them 
still he said strugnell had agreed to a timetable that would 
see the remaining documents published by 1997 
an estimated 800 scrolls have been recovered but many are in 
fragments eight scrolls are displayed at the israel museum the 
remainder are in the rockefeller museum 
</TEXT>
