<TEXT>
a landmark commissions attempt to regulate 
changes inside a jesuit church in the citys historic south end 
violated the free exercise of religion the states highest court 
ruled monday 
the government interest in historic preservation though 
worthy is not sufficiently compelling to justify restraints on the 
free exercise of religion a right of primary importance the 
state supreme judicial court said in a unanimous opinion 
the dispute revolved around the designation of the interior of 
the church of the immaculate conception as a landmark there are 
fewer finer examples of classic mid19th century church design 
the court said in its opinion 
the national trust for historic preservation the american 
jewish congress and the council on religious freedom were among 
groups that filed friend of the court briefs in the case 
in 1986 the jesuits developed a plan to renovate the aging 
church and build an office counseling and residential space 
when the renovation work began 10 registered city voters 
promptly petitioned the boston landmarks commission to designate 
the interior of the 127yearold church as a landmark 
the granite church is located near boston city hospital and 
once served boston college students before the school moved out of 
the city said father paul kenney a spokesman for the society of 
jesus of new england 
its overall impression is one of light kenney said of the 
structures interior 
in 1987 the commission approved the landmark designation for 
portions of the church the designation made any permanent 
alteration of the nave vestibule chancel and organ loft on the 
main floor as well as other architectural details subject to the 
commissions approval 
under the designation the jesuits were only allowed to install 
nonpermanent furnishings and to conduct routine maintenance inside 
the church 
the commission eventually allowed the jesuits to make some 
renovations to the interior but in the meantime the jesuits filed 
a lawsuit contending the landmark designation was unconstitutional 
in a unanimous ruling the supreme judicial court agreed but 
the court framed the decision narrowly referring only to a section 
of the massachusetts constitution 
the decision did not refer to federal guarantees of religious 
freedom the court also made no ruling on the preservation of 
church exteriors noting the case dealt only with a church 
interior 
under our hierarchy of constitutional values we must accept 
the possible loss of historically significant elements of the 
interior of this church as the price of safeguarding the right of 
religious freedom the court said 
edward hanify an attorney who represented the jesuits said the 
case represents a key decision for all denominations 
im delighted that we have what i would say is a historic and 
compelling decision about religious freedom hanify said 
john kenneth felter the attorney for the landmark commission 
said he could not comment on the case until he discussed the 
outcome with his clients 
andrea ferster an attorney for the national trust for historic 
preservation said the ruling is narrow enough so that its impact 
nationally is muted 
</TEXT>
