recent agreement between italy and albania the last of the 
hardline communist regimes in eastern europe but italian 
government officials reached monday said they had no knowledge of 
any such agreement 
the italian embassy in tirana said it had issued 37 visas for 
albanian jews and that it did not have any applications for others 
israeli government officials were tightlipped about the 
immigration of albanian jews apparently fearful of harming the 
effort 
this is going to save albanian jews from total extinction had 
they remained there they would have been wiped out in a 
generation said rabbi marc tanenbaum a consultant to the 
american jewish committee in new york 
the albanian jewish community numbers only about 1000 
officials said 
greek foreign minister andonis samaras appealed to ethnic greeks 
to remain in albania and enjoy the fruits of democracy as 
reforms are introduced 
the albanian government of president ramiz alia has promised 
such reforms as allowing religious services and the establishment 
of opposition parties but the refugees say they do not have faith 
in the promises 
we didnt believe alia said zisis karkasainas a 
26yearold economics graduate 
greek officials estimate about 350000 of albanias 33 million 
people are ethnic greeks the strain of the sudden influx can 
already be seen in the border towns 
ive been working 24 hours a day for a week now we dont have 
enough food for all these people said a woman who identified 
herself only as anastasia she was in charge of a kitchen in an old 
orphanage that has been trying to feed all the albanians who have 
crossed the border in the last two days 
dozens of refugees waited in a long line outside the orphange 
police estimated that 95 percent of the albanians who crossed 
the border are ethnic greeks who lived in frontier villages ethnic 
greeks are given temporary residence permits while the other 
albanians are taken to a united nations refugee center outside 
athens 
most of them crossed the border near filiates a town of 5000 
because the terrain is less mountainous than elsewhere along the 
100mile border 
they should declare a state of emergency up here we cant 
cope any more said father zilis the town priest he and three 
other residents formed a committee to help the refugees with food 
clothing and shelter 
the mayor pantelis koufalas on sunday sent a telex to premier 
constantine mitsotakis pleading for assistance 
a small greek army border detachment began cooking for the 
refugees after a makeshift soup kitchen ran out of food and groups 
of refugees tried to force their way into the orphanage 
look at them your heart breaks but what more can we do 
committee member nikolas georgopoulos said 
most of the refugees wearing donated clothes sat in the mud 
outside the orphanage 
shepherd ilias bouros brought his wife two infant children a 
65yearold grandmother and a nephew to greece from the town of 
sarande 
i walked 18 hours to get here with my family he said 
were tired but happy to get out of albania 
