<TEXT>
when gov michael s dukakis took over 
massachusetts from a republican governor the economy was spiraling 
downward and the state budget was mired in red ink 
sixteen years later dukakis passes the reins to another 
republican and returns the fiscal favor the economy is in the 
cellar and the dukes successor william weld faces painful budget 
cuts or tax increases 
dukakis leaves office thursday as the longest serving governor 
in state history his threeterm tenure interrupted for four 
years from 1979 to 1983 is studded with accomplishments and 
controversy political heights and electoral disaster 
but the fiscal and economic condition of massachusetts that 
dukakis leaves behind mirrors the circumstances he inherited in 
1975 as a hardcharging cando reformer 
it looks to me as an outsider as though its a hell of a lot 
worse mess now said former gov francis w sargent who planned 
to attend thursdays inaugural and welcome in the first republican 
governor of massachusetts since he lost to dukakis 
when the duke came in i think he had an idea that he was 
going to be able to bring the budget home and spread it out on the 
kitchen table and figure out where he could cut sargent said 
dukakis promised no new taxes in his 1974 gubernatorial 
campaign and when he took office he adopted as a symbol a meat 
cleaver that he said would be needed to cut state government down 
to size he promised a herculean effort to reduce expenditures 
to eliminate waste 
but dukakis and his fiscal advisers discovered that the state 
was in deep financial trouble hundreds of millions in medicaid 
bills were unpaid the state welfare department was in debt a 
modest surplus of six months earlier became early in 1975 a 
deficit of between 350 million and 500 million a huge chunk in 
a state whos total budget was about 3 billion 
with unemployment at 112 percent and with oil prices soaring 
amid the arab oil embargo the state economy was in no condition to 
bail out state government 
less than a year after taking office dukakis had to eat his 
campaign promise and back the largest tax increase in the states 
history 
the parallels in massachusetts today are startling 
oil prices are again on the rise pushed by a different crisis 
in the mideast unemployment is increasing though it has not yet 
reached the doubledigit levels of the mid1970s and once again 
the problems confronting massachusetts coincide with a national 
economic slump and with similar fiscal crises elsewhere 
dukakis disputes those who predict he will leave behind a large 
deficit 
there is no comparison dukakis said in an interview monday 
in 1975 we were looking at a budget deficit that was 25 percent 
of the total 
in the past few months dukakis has been able to present his 
successor with a detailed appraisal of the states fiscal 
condition 
in 75 we didnt have that kind of information dukakis 
said nobody paid attention to monthly revenue estimates back 
then 
still massachusetts does face the prospect of a sizable 
deficit some state legislators have estimated the state would wind 
up some 300 million in the red at the end of the fiscal year next 
june governorelect weld said this week his advisers put the 
deficit as high as 750 million 
weld bound himself to a nonewtaxes promise much as dukakis 
did in 1975 weld is talking about laying off public employees to 
balance the books 
and the state legislature is in no mood to consider a tax 
increase 
in 1975 the legislature was dominated by liberal democrats who 
had no qualms about raising taxes and indeed urged dukakis to 
abandon his nonewtaxes pledge 
todays legislature still has a majority of democrats and some 
surviving liberals but theyre wary of voters who are in no mood 
to shell out more tax dollars 
</TEXT>
