<TEXT>
six prominent saudi men in a rare 
public airing of views spoke monday of overzealous religious 
police a demonstration by women drivers that backfired and fears 
that war would destroy their country 
the significance of the news conference was not so much in the 
saudis views which largely reflect the governments positions 
but in the fact that they agreed to talk on the record news 
conferences by saudi citizens were unheard of before iraqs 
invasion of kuwait because few journalists were allowed into the 
country and because saudis are reluctant to freely state their 
opinions 
the hourlong news conference covered everything from gas masks 
for foreign workers to the possibility of a permanent us military 
presence in saudi arabia as well as windfall profits from rising 
oil prices and production 
but it was the possibility of war with iraq an arab brother 
nation that the saudis had supported with 20 billion during the 
eightyear war with iran that stirred their emotions 
the united nations has set a deadline of jan 15 for iraq to 
withdraw from kuwait or face a possible military attack 
salih a altoaimi secretary general of the chamber of commerce 
in riyadh said he was praying for a miracle that saddam 
hussein will withdraw peacefully from kuwait 
i personally think it will happen he said 
nobody wants war i think the highest price ever paid by 
everybody will be much much cheaper than the consequences of war 
so we all should do our best to avoid it he said all people 
are concerned and hate to see our country and even iraq 
destroyed 
dr ali alnamlah an associate professor at imam mohammed bin 
saud islamic university in riyadh said the saudis are ready 
psychologically to face the consequences of war but hope for 
peace 
we are waiting for miracles to happen we are waiting for a 
tough decision by the ruler of iraq he said 
the deployment of more than 300000 us troops has opened a 
window however small in this conservative moslem country where 
alcohol is banned and women must be completely covered in public 
dr fahad alsamari a professor of economics and political 
science at the islamic university said he had studied the presence 
of us troops in vietnam and there was a definite difference in 
their behavior here 
we have seen the american troops are behaving very well he 
said they have been briefed they are following the rules 
respecting the culture respecting the saudis respecting the norms 
and traditions here 
but like the other saudis he said all foreign troops must 
leave as soon as kuwait is liberated and the country must build a 
large army to defend itself 
every society doesnt want any foreigners to stay in that 
military aspect he explained if you have a house and you have 
a soldier by your house you want it from the family not outside 
the family who doesnt know your system or understand you 
the ministry of information arranged the news conference in 
response to requests from some of the hundreds of journalists 
covering the us military buildup who wanted to get a saudi 
civilian perspective on the gulf crisis all six of the 
participants spoke fluent english 
since the arrival of us troops there has been a westernstyle 
demonstration by about 40 saudi women who drove through riyadh to 
protest a ban on women driving 
there has also been a crackdown by the religious police called 
the muttawa who have invaded several private homes where parties 
were being held 
alnamlah said the muttawas role was to control society for 
anything which violates islamic law and they probably had 
authorization to break into peoples homes 
but ibrahim altouq chairman of the riyadh chamber of commerce 
said the muttawa just had a role in keeping certain traditions and 
religious teachings and in certain instances i think they overdo 
it 
many saudis dont agree with people breaking into houses 
without any reason he said we were very much concerned about 
this becoming more extreme or more the rule rather than the 
exception and we expressed our views to the departments concerned 
and im sure they understood the concern of the people 
although there is nothing in islamic law against women driving 
the ban is a saudi tradition and altouqsaid the women should have 
tested public opinion first and tried to win support instead of 
springing the protest 
the very conservative people were surprised and were scared of 
such a thing they thought this was maybe the beginning of lets 
say a revolution or something very bad happening he said 
some of the women who were professors have been suspended from 
their jobs and all the women have been banned from traveling 
outside the country 
