the editor of a student newspaper said 
she hopes a federal judge will rule on her lawsuit to open campus 
crime reports in time to publish the information in the papers 
next issue on jan 18 
lawyers for both sides filed briefs with us district judge 
russell g clark on dec 21 
arguments were filed after lawyers douglas w greene who 
represents traci bauer and the southwest standard of southwest 
missouri state university and john f black who represents the 
school were unable to reach a settlement 
the issue centers on whether ms bauer can have access to 
university crime reports and whether releasing those reports will 
threaten the schools ability to receive federal funds 
in his brief greene contends the universitys resistance to ms 
bauers effort to get crime reports is indicative of the schools 
refusal to acknowledge crimes occur on campus he said the 
university has refused the springfield police departments offer to 
station two officers on campus 
greene also argues that administrators are more concerned about 
image than informing students and the public of crimes on campus 
he asked the judge to rule that the university is a public body 
and comes under state open meeting and records laws 
black countered in his brief that a ruling for the newspaper 
would open the prospect of requiring every university department to 
make all documents and proceedings available to the public past 
court cases have ruled that while the board of regents is a public 
body governed by the states open records law a university is not 
subject to that law he wrote 
trying to comply with the federal family education and privacy 
rights act while satisfying ms bauers demand for access to crime 
reports would not work because the university would have to notify 
students an exception had been made to the federal act black said 
ms bauer has been given oral reports of crimes by campus 
security officers black said to go beyond that would violate the 
privacy of others he said 
