civil suit claiming phoenix police destroyed records that could 
help prove his innocence 
in a 30 ruling dec 27 the state court of appeals said the 
lawsuit was filed by max dunlap too long after the fact to qualify 
under the statute of limitations 
dunlap was convicted in 1977 of killing bolles a reporter for 
the arizona republic dunlaps conviction was overturned on appeal 
in 1980 but he was charged again on dec 19 he is accused of 
ordering the slaying at the behest of unidentified higherups 
he filed his civil lawsuit on july 2 1982 claiming his 
constitutional rights were violated when police shredded documents 
in the case 
a superior court judge threw out the suit in 1988 saying its 
filing two years and a month after the dismissal of the first 
criminal charge was a month too late 
dunlap argued on appeal that he had three years in which to file 
because the statute of limitations for fraud cases is three years 
and the suit claims police officers engaged in fraud 
but appeals judge william eubank said that the suit really 
centered on the claim dunlaps constitutional rights were violated 
and that such claims must be brought to court within two years 
dunlaps lawyer murray miller said he had to study the 
decision before deciding whether to appeal the state supreme court 
