<TEXT>
the economics staff of the federal trade 
commission said dec 26 that it again had urged the fcc to abolish 
rules that keep broadcast television networks from owning program 
rerun rights 
the ftcs economics bureau first urged abolition of the rules in 
september it expanded its comments to include several proposed 
modifications of the financial interest and syndication rules 
which commonly are called finsyn 
one proposal would regulate negotiations between program 
producers and networks negotiations about which the economists 
said we do not find compelling reasons to adopt any of the 
proposed restrictions 
a proposal that would modify but not abolish the rules may 
lead to a result that is less desirable than either complete 
elimination or complete retention of the rules the bureau said 
our analysis of these options leads us to continue to believe 
that the best course for the fcc is to repeal completely the 
existing finsyn rules the bureau said 
the justice department also has said the rules should be 
eliminated 
the fcc plans to decide in 1991 whether to keep junk or change 
the rules which were adopted 20 years ago when the broadcast 
networks had a much larger share of the primetime viewing audience 
than they have today 
the rules permit the networks to own only the overseas rerun 
rights to the primetime shows they produce themselves and bar the 
networks from any financial interest in other primetime programs 
including offnetwork or syndicated showings 
the ftcs economics bureau comments frequently on proposed 
regulations of other federal agencies and state agencies generally 
urging views that would result in increased competition 
</TEXT>
