<TEXT>
david frost preparing for the interview with 
president and mrs bush that airs tonight on pbs was delighted to 
share his knowledge on the art of the interview 
tonights hourlong talking with david frost is the 
first in a series of six by frost 50 a twotime emmy award winner 
known here since the weekly satire that was the week that was 
aired on us tv in 1964 
it was frost who in 1977 won worldwide attention with his 
series of interviews with former president richard nixon 
future talking episodes will feature margaret thatcher and 
entertainer robin williams tonights interview with the bushes was 
not available at press time here then is the david frost short 
course on the interview 
ts eliot said a work of art has a life of its own frost 
said settling back into his chair although i wouldnt claim 
that an interview is a work of art it does have a life of its 
own 
i preparation is important 
some people think the more preparation you do the more it 
shackles you to a prepared plan he said the truth of good 
homework or good research is it liberates you to go with the flow 
of the interview 
the less you know the more you have to stick to your set 
questions 
the other thing is it saves you from boring the pants off 
somebody 
frost said he and a staff of four compiled three thick binders 
of research and background for tonights interview with the first 
couple from that frost transposes his questions background and 
quotes onto cardboard folders 
on those folders theres a game plan but it aint sacred 
he said 
for the famed nixon interviews which yielded six hours of 
television from 28 hours of interviews over 12 days frost said he 
had four journalists working for a year to prepare for it 
ii know when to shut up 
there are silences in interviews and in television 
interviews silence is an eternity he said there are two 
sorts of silences one is where you just sense that if you shut up 
the person will go on and say perhaps more than they were going to 
say 
and then theres another sort of silence where you realize the 
person has forgotten completely what the hell they were going to 
say and that silence is one that youd better fill as fast as 
possible 
iii the importance of listening 
obviously the most important thing is listening that is so 
transparently obvious that it seems unnecessary to say it but so 
many times people have said to me its so good that you really 
listen so i guess not everybody does 
he recalled being interviewed in england by a radio host who 
followed a questions list without listening to the answers frost 
said at first he tried to be kind saying im glad you got back 
to that he soon tired of it 
in the end it got irresistible i ended one answer by saying 
and then of course i married the popes first wife and the guy 
said but what do you feel about the future of the common 
market 
iv turn an interview into a conversation as soon as possible 
thats so theres interplay so that both people become 
absorbed in the conversation he said i dont mean they become 
absorbed in the conversation to the point where they forget 
themselves but where they forget the cameras the lights and so 
on 
v on being lied to 
there are occasions when you do have to become not just the 
catalyst but the principal he said and that is when you feel 
to use a splendid euphemism that the facts are being done a 
disservice churchill used the phrase when you feel someone is 
guilty of a terminological inexactitude 
in those circumstances you do have to become a principal and 
then you do have to press and then you do have to repeat the 
question and then you do have to repeat the facts that you think 
contradict what the persons just said and sometimes you have to 
return to it again and again and say but yes but 
vi on the roles of the interviewer 
you do sometimes have to adopt varying roles frost said 
he cited the first day of the nixon interviews in which nixon 
stonewalled questions about the watergate affair 
it was prosecution and defense frost said when he came 
back on the second day having realized the total stonewall did not 
work he was prepared to volunteer something not enough as it 
turned out and then suddenly the atmosphere became more of the 
confessional 
then on an entirely different subject the breakthrough to 
china there i was boswell to his johnson 
vii on having paid nixon to be interviewed 
i paid 600000 for six hours on the air and nbc news who 
were the semifinalists as it were the runnersup had offered 
400000 for two hours so i wasnt the only person who doing it 
so i offered more money but i got a better rate per hour 
 
elsewhere in television 
and speaking of that was the week that was dept nbcs 
planned debut of sunday best a comedic review of the week on 
tv was to be jan 13 a sunday 
then it was pushed back to feb 3 to the suicide slot opposite 
cbs 60 minutes 
the network cited uncertainties of postseason football games 
that could delay the start of sunday best and affect the 
premiere of dark shadows the fourhour tv movie airing on jan 
1314 
