<TEXT>
james and rikki pomerenke fought to make 
the nations food safer as a result they no longer feel safe 
the truckdrivers keep five loaded guns in their yakima home for 
protection unemployed for more than a year they contend they have 
been blackballed by the local trucking industry because they 
exposed the practice of hauling toxic chemicals and food products 
in the same tankers 
with fellow truckers dave helzer and sharon sonner they 
revealed that some trucking companies required drivers to deliver 
dangerous chemicals in one load then wash out the tanker and fill 
it with food grade products on the backhaul 
their whistleblowing resulted in a new federal law signed in 
early november by president bush that restricted such crosshauling 
practices 
the law requires clear labeling to identify tankers for sole use 
with foods or chemicals it also gives truckers the right to refuse 
an illegal backhaul 
the law will increase the down time for truckers making it more 
difficult to get lucrative backhauls the pomerenkes said 
still cliff harvison president of national tank truck carriers 
inc in alexandria va said much of the industry supports what 
the pomerenkes did 
they are good decent honest moral people harvison said 
they did the right thing 
but doing the right thing has not made life easy for the 
pomerenkes they say they have been ostracized by friends and are 
running out of money they claim that they have been threatened 
and warned by former coworkers that they could face physical harm 
we are at the end of our rope said pomerenke 45 
its real hard for me to deal with said rikki pomerenke 
40 we dont have any friends anymore 
the central washington city of 55000 is a major producer of 
fruits and vegetables with a large trucking industry 
down here people didnt have an axe to grind and were not 
bound economically with the fruit and agriculture community of 
yakima ms sonner said theres loose cannons any place and 
any time 
helzer and sonner have left yakima they moved to hermiston 
ore after the publicity started to overwhelm them and after 
helzers truck was broken into twice while they did not feel they 
had been blackballed they thought there were better prospects for 
steady employment elsewhere ms sonner said 
the pomerenkes are longtime residents of yakima they have 
family there and they dont want to move 
they contend they have applied to numerous trucking companies 
for jobs and are turned down as soon as the employer learns who 
they are they declined to name any of the trucking companies 
the pomerenkes acknowledged there has been at least one local 
job offer but they turned it down because the pay was less than 
the prevailing scale 
the pomerenkes live on a 1500 per month disability check for a 
hand injury rikki suffered while operating a jackhammer on a 
construction job last year james receives unemployment 
ms sonner said neither couple was aware of the attention their 
whistleblowing would bring 
in all honesty i dont think the four of us would have had 
enough nerve to go through with it ms sonner said its scary 
to have someone from dc call up and say please testify before 
congress 
the pomerenkes have filed a lawsuit against their former 
employer in yakima county superior court the lawsuit contends that 
former employer premium transport has hurt their ability to get 
work by unlawful termination outrageous conduct defamation and 
breach of contract 
that company is defunct former president james ketchum also a 
defendant in the lawsuit has declined to return numerous telephone 
messages 
the pomerenkes had been construction workers in the yakima area 
for about 15 years when they decided to seek steady employment 
together as a longhaul driving team in late 1987 
what we learned in the year and a half made me sick said 
mrs pomerenke 
the lawsuit contends they were asked to lie about their previous 
load when using tanker washing facilities and to lie to shippers 
about their most recent load when picking up food after hauling 
chemicals 
they hauled juice wine and milk after hauling items like 
inedible tallow and plastic resin which is used to make foam 
insulation 
in may 1989 the pomerenkes refused to haul a chemical from the 
midwest to the west coast returning with their empty tanker to 
yakima they were fired 
they are angry about the treatment they have received since they 
went to washington to testify 
im an american and i love my country and its obvious from 
what weve done that we care about it james pomerenke said 
its strange that there are no laws to protect people who step 
forward 
