<TEXT>
 
editors note their former leaders are scattered they are 
bickering among themselves and dramatic political upheavals around 
the globe have overshadowed their cause chinas prodemocracy 
activists are struggling to keep alive the spirit of tiananmen 
square 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
chinas prodemocracy movement which seized the 
hearts and attention of the world a year and a half ago at 
tiananmen square is faltering 
internal squabbling chinas reestablishment in the world 
community and the international medias preoccupation with eastern 
europe and the persian gulf have nudged democracy activists out of 
the headlines public interest has waned 
the most prominent student leaders of the massive protests that 
engulfed beijing now lead lowprofile lives far from the spotlight 
that made them media stars and one of them a nobel peace prize 
nominee 
wuer kaixi the eloquent but mercurial firebrand has been 
pumping gas near san francisco chai ling whose impassioned 
leadership in the protests final days won her the nobel 
nomination has left her husband fellow student dissident leader 
feng congde in paris and is quietly attending princeton 
university 
without them the movement has lost much of its cachet 
wan runnan newly elected president of the federation for a 
democratic china concedes that public support has diminished 
but there are bound to be periods of high and low interest 
he said in an interview no one can ignore a country that 
represents onefourth of the worlds population 
the federation was born amid much fanfare in paris in september 
1989 two months after the bicentennial of the french revolution 
the annual parade down the champs elysees was led by some 200 
chinese students on bicycles momentarily giving paris most famous 
street the look of a beijing boulevard 
chinese soldiers backed by tanks charged down those beijing 
boulevards in the early morning of june 4 1989 shooting and 
killing at least several hundred unarmed protesters the searing 
images of the bloodshed were etched into the minds of millions who 
watched the tragey unfold on television 
much of the protests leadership fled overseas as had decades 
before them the influential political thinkers kang youwei and 
his disciple liang qichao and sun yatsen the founder of modern 
china all were active in japan preaching democracy for china 
around the turn of the century 
exile abroad was also the lot of former premier zhou enlai 
revered by the students at tiananmen and recently retired senior 
leader deng xiaoping despised by the democracy supporters as the 
mastermind of the crackdown they began their revolutionary careers 
in france where they joined the communist party in the early 
1920s 
the federation has kept its dream of chinese democracy alive 
through seminars demonstrations and criticism of chinas 
authoritarian regime 
its founders include dissidents forced to leave china such as 
physicist fang lizhi who hid in beijings us embassy for more 
than a year before being allowed to leave and outspoken marxist 
theoretician su shaozhi who for years advocated thorough reform of 
the communist party 
it has maintained contacts in china and closely monitors what it 
claims are continuing human rights abuses under chinas communist 
government 
recently it spearheaded denunciations of the trials of top 
dissidents in china the federation said the trials violated 
chinas constitution by holding the accused for 13 months without 
trial and denying them defense lawyers of their choice 
wang juntao and chen ziming who published a dissident magazine 
are accused of sedition which carries a maximum penalty of death 
wang dan the student seen as the behindthescenes brain of the 
popular movement stands accused of counterrevolutionary 
incitement 
but the dissident movement in exile has lost the momentum that 
used to attract large crowds and donations at its rallies and 
fundraisers 
the formation of the fdc the federation came at a high tide 
for the democracy movement says andrew nathan a professor at 
columbia university in new york and author of two books on chinese 
democracy 
there were signs that the chinese regime would collapse and 
the cream of the crop were organizing overseas there were a lot of 
expectations but things didnt happen 
the federation is regrouping and seeking fresh directions under 
wan elected at the groups annual convention in san francisco he 
directs chapters in 20 countries formed most recently in brazil 
and greece from a threeroom office in a quiet section of 
northwest paris 
he insists the group has been effective 
without an opposition faction there will never be 
democracy he says if the united states didnt have two 
parties if poland hadnt had solidarity you couldnt have 
democracy there cannot be a rule that the chinese communist party 
must be in power 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP901231-0163 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
his top priority is to persuade foreign governments to pressure 
beijing toward greater political liberalization and respect for 
human rights he is disappointed that the west has dropped most of 
the economic and political sanctions imposed against china so soon 
after the crackdown 
we understand part of their reasons he says but as for 
the conditions that brought on the sanctions in the first place 
the suppression the arrests there has been absolutely no 
change 
wan hopes to strengthen the movement through increased 
cooperation with overseas chinese and other opposition 
organizations but he faces criticism from rival dissident groups 
wan runnan is shortsighted and an opportunist he thinks that 
just by eliminating the communists oneparty rule youll have 
democracy in china says wang xiaoyu a former reporter for the 
government news agency xinhua who is now chief editor for the 
dissident house of chinese democracy also in paris 
the blood from june 4 hasnt yet dried and hes setting up a 
small clique of intellectuals who consider themselves the 
government in exile they make a lot of statements but dont do 
anything constructive 
wan 46 believes he will see democracy in china within his 
lifetime but wang says that is simplistic and that it could 
take 200 even 500 years 
disagreements arise within the federation itself 
on the eve of the san francisco convention a faction within the 
federation criticized wan their candidate to oppose wan was 
elected federation vice president 
wan is a former software engineer with the chinese academy of 
sciences computer center who in 1984 was named head of the stone 
corp chinas first private hightechnology firm a strong 
supporter of the students at tiananmen he defected while visiting 
hong kong four days after the crackdown when he learned an arrest 
warrant had been issued for him 
he took over as federation president from yan jiaqi who as a 
former adviser to ousted communist party chief zhao ziyang had 
respectable credentials but was more theorist than organizer 
among wans tasks is addressing problems of the federations 
first year 
the fdc hasnt been particularly effective in lobbying 
nathan says reaching out to the nonchinese community is 
something theyve proved theyre not very good at doing 
there was also the fiasco of the goddess of democracy a ship 
which was to broadcast prodemocracy messages into china but is now 
a tourist attraction drawing mild interest in taiwan the mission 
floundered when neither japan nor taiwan would allow the activists 
to load a radio transmitter on board 
the federations finances reportedly have suffered more from 
bad administration than malfeasance of the 1 million the 
federation received in its first year it spent only 3 percent on 
expanding democracy activities and 40 percent on travel or 
consultations according to the chineselanguage european daily 
news 
when chai ling visited the united states this past summer she 
raised 40000 but spent virtually all of it paying for the trip 
according to a chinese paper in the united states 
wan also has to make up for the departure from france of chai 
ling and wuer kaixi whose youthful zeal made them strong media 
draws 
yet wuer was a dubious asset to the organization because of 
reports of his flamboyant lifestyle 
wuer kaixi ruined the fdcs reputation by spending too much 
money on food and taxis wang says 
wuer now works at a gas station near san francisco and is 
applying to attend the university of california at berkeley 
things havent been too tough for me over the past year he 
said during a recent trip to taiwan i thought it wouldnt hurt 
to do something humble for awhile 
about wuer and chai wan says you cant base a political 
movement on stars their departure is a maturing process both 
for them and for us 
wan himself was exploring the possibility of returning to 
beijing according to a us diplomat he left behind a wife and 
collegestudent son they were not arrested but cannot leave the 
capital 
wan says only that he considered returning to china to continue 
working for democratic reforms from within but abandoned the idea 
yet with limited ability in french and english he admits thinking 
often of home 
people of that age their lives revolve around china nathan 
says theyve spent a lifetime achieving a stature that they will 
never gain overseas they now have an agonizing choice over what to 
do with their lives 
sitting around drumming their fingers living off of 
fellowships how long can this go on 
