editors note for more than three decades before it closed 
the cotter corp mill in colorado processed uranium for nuclear 
power plants it has been cited nearly 100 times by both state and 
federal officials for allegedly polluting the mill site and the 
surrounding area now residents of one neighborhood near the mill 
have gone to court with a 550 million lawsuit 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
sitting in the calicocovered swing on 
their back porch watching their horse trot around her pen near the 
red barn nard and sara claar seem to be living the american dream 
fruit trees and flowers cover their acre of land and not far 
away are the rocky mountains cold streams and deep forests 
sara 38 grew up here in the lincoln park subdivision on the 
edge of canon city a city of 13000 in southern colorado she and 
nard 40 never gave much thought to the cotter corp uranium mill 
less than two miles from their home 
cotter was considered a solid citizen next to the state prison 
system and its halfdozen facilities the mill was canon citys 
largest employer in its heyday the mill owned by chicagobased 
commonwealth edison employed 250 people and processed 1200 tons 
of rock a day 
that was before sarah became ill and 13 people on their block 
were diagnosed as having cancer or had died of it 
now the claars and many of the nearly 400 people who live in 
lincoln park think their neighborhood has been contaminated by 
cotters uranium processing 
we just thought this was a natural occurrence everybody knew 
somebody who died of cancer says sara who only recently became 
able to work around her home after being bedridden 18 months with 
immune deficiency problems four members of her family have cancer 
but now the claars and their neighbors believe cotter whose 
mill here is listed as a superfund cleanup site by the 
environmental protection agency is the culprit they note that in 
its 32 years the cotter mill has been cited nearly 100 times by 
both state and federal officials for allegedly polluting the mill 
site and surrounding areas 
the uranium mill has been closed since 1987 because its product 
uranium concentrate called yellowcake for nuclear power 
plants is no longer in demand no date has been set for 
operations to resume 
the mill crushed ground and leached uranium with acid to 
convert it to yellowcake dumping the leftovers into piles next to 
the mill or in ponds used to control dust cotter operated one mill 
at the site from 1958 to 1979 then opened a newer bigger one 
nearby because of growing demand for their product 
the mill site also wound up as the repository of 250 kilograms 
of radioactive leftovers from the first atomic bomb called the 
st louis airport cakes because thats where the tailings were 
stored initially cotter purchased the cakes in 1968 and shipped 
the radioactive residue which contained the rare cancercausing 
radioactive isotope thorium230 to canon city in open railroad 
cars 
cotter processed nearly twothirds of the cakes to extract their 
uranium copper cobalt and nickel the leftovers were dumped into 
a lined holding pond at the mill 
a 1986 state report said there were holes in the pond lining 
that allowed contaminated water to leach into the ground water 
cotters image as a model corporate citizen began to erode when 
traces of radioactive uranium began showing up in well water in 
lincoln park apparently water contaminated with the uranium had 
seeped into the ground water beneath the mill and then had migrated 
to lincoln park airborne uranium dust added to the problem 
about the time cotter was eyeing a bigger operation to take 
advantage of rising uranium prices regulators were starting to 
take a closer look at cotters pollution problems 
the colorado bureau of investigation cited cotter in 1980 for 
repeatedly overexposing its workers to uranium dust and for 
falsifying occupational health data in reports to the state health 
department the same year the health department accused cotter of 
23 violations of its state radioactive materials license 
the nuclear regulatory commission in january 1981 recommended 
that several lincoln park residents stop using well water for 
irrigation and their livestock because of possible contamination 
from the cotter mill 
in march 1986 a study commissioned by the state and done by 
geotransrocky mountain consultants inc found that mining and 
milling activities at cotter had seriously contaminated the 
surrounding area 
in august 1988 the state sent a letter to fremont county 
officials saying lincoln park residents face a potential health 
risk because of contamination from the cotter mill 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP901231-0167 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
cotter today is cleaning up the mill site as part of an 11 
million environmental damage settlement reached in 1988 with the 
state of colorado 
phil stoffey the onsite cleanup coordinator for the state 
health departments radiation control division estimates it will 
take cotter 20 years to clean up the site under the remedial action 
plan 
the company also faces a major lawsuit filed by lincoln park 
residents in august 1989 their anger over what they believe is a 
high cancer rate and over cotters pollution problems spilled over 
into a 550 million lawsuit filed in federal court in denver the 
lawsuit claims uranium waste from the mill polluted the ground 
water and was carried on the wind causing damage to residents 
health and property 
nard claar thinks cotter was given too much leeway in how much 
uranium waste it could discharge into the air 30 tons per year 
what happens to that it blows over my house and my neighbors 
house he says to my knowledge the cotter corp didnt use us 
as guinea pigs but with 30 tons of uranium being allowed there 
was a radioactive cloud over this valley 
the state cancer register does not show an aboveaverage 
incidence of the disease among fremont county residents and the 
state does not keep data on individual cities or neighborhoods 
state health officials say it is difficult to assess the cancer 
risk from exposure to cotters uranium mill wastes 
its longrange and lowlevel says ken weaver of the 
radiation control division were not talking about the kind of 
radioactivity where spending a few hours or days in front of 
the uranium pile will cause cancer its the longrange longterm 
effects on health 
a 1981 federal study found evidence of kidney damage in 29 men 
who worked at cotter and a 1987 attorney generals report said 
lincoln park residents are receptors at risk if they drink 
contaminated water eat food irrigated with contaminated water or 
grown in contaminated soil or inhale dust or radon from mill 
sources 
the state in 1988 issued a warning that said lincoln park 
residents face a potential health risk by drinking water 
contaminated by the mill many lincoln park residents got their 
water from wells whose water later was found to be contaminated 
with uranium and molybdenum a byproduct of uranium processing 
while lincoln park residents press their concerns in court 
opinion is more divided among other canon city residents 
everybody living in fremont county is not cowering and 
concerned that they will get cancer says pat sherwood executive 
director of the canon city chamber of commerce she says the media 
have implied that the entire community is concerned about becoming 
ill and its just not true 
jack rothfleisch the cotter mill manager who is supervising the 
site cleanup does not think the cancer rate is any higher in 
lincoln park than anyplace else 
i think those people would have cancer if they were in the 
middle of nebraska too he says as far as im concerned i 
dont think anybody has been harmed in any way by the exposure to 
what weve done out here 
cotter officials would not discuss the lawsuit but they were 
willing to speak about the companys special relationship with 
canon city 
the relationship of the cotter corp with the community has 
been a close enduring one in which the company and the community 
have shared in some good times and some bad times says joe 
mccluskey cotter vice president and general manager of the 
companys lakewood office 
the company and its employees have always appreciated the 
support of the community and likewise the community has enjoyed 
the support of the cotter corp over many years 
meanwhile sara claar is seeking treatment in denver for her 
undiagnosed illness nard and sara say one of their greatest 
frustrations is not knowing what they face 
i cannot say that cotter made me sick mrs claar says 
but id like to know what did weve never been able to get a 
definite answer now at least theyre testing 
</TEXT>
