editors note not all park rangers roam the wilds keeping a 
lookout for forest fires and wayward bears at independence hall in 
philadelphia the rangers of the national park service are more like 
classroom teachers than caretakers of nature and theyd better 
know their history 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
national park service rangers at 
independence hall still remember the woman who insisted on seeing 
the statue of liberty 
people really do think of philadelphia as the cradle of 
liberty and some visitors think its all here says ranger larry 
mcclennie this lady insisted that the statue was here somewhere 
she wanted directions to find it and go 100 miles north and turn 
right wasnt what she wanted 
even if the no 1 question is wheres the bathroom the 
rangers who show off the liberty bell and independence hall need to 
be ready to answer all kinds of questions from some 14 million 
visitors a year 
i probably learned more history here than i ever could have 
imagined says scott dawson whos worked two seasonal stints at 
the park 
a question that comes up a lot is how the bell cracked after it 
rang for years in the statehouse tower to announce important events 
such as the signing of the declaration of independence 
cracks in bells were fairly common in those days mcclennie 
explains they were repaired and put back in service as the 
liberty bell was but it cracked again and wasnt used after 
that 
the park which encompasses nearly two dozen buildings that 
figured in the birth of the united states as a nation has a guide 
staff of 40 rangers 70 in the peak months from april through 
september 
wouldbe rangers go through a week of intensive training 
according to barbara pollarine director of interpretation they 
learn about three themes the american revolution benjamin 
franklin and philadelphia as the national capital 
after a day of lectures and exercises the rangerstudents 
tackle a long reading list 
there are standard texts such as miracle at philadelphia by 
catherine drinker bowen another is the liberty bell the 
venerable relic by former park historian dave kimball 
rangers are also encouraged to do research in the libraries of 
the pennsylvania historical society the american philosophical 
society and the park itself resources not available anywhere else 
by the end of their first week each new ranger is expected to 
deliver a brief presentation prepared for the public 
the trainees learn the basic history of the buildings but when 
they speak to the public as rangers they add their own flair to 
the presentation to make it interesting to the visitors says david 
dutcher chief historian of the park 
when dawson leads a tour of independence hall he explains that 
so much of the interior is green because it was the cheapest dye in 
the 18th century 
then he points out his uniform green and wonders whether the 
government is still as cheap as it used to be 
other rangers tell of the haunted second floor of congress hall 
the ghost of french queen marie antoinette supposedly lurks there 
no one knows how the story got started but king louis xvi of 
france did donate a painting of his wife to congress and the 
painting was lost in the move to washington a reproduction of the 
painting now hangs in congress hall in philadelphia 
as popular as this park is with the public its the biggest 
tourist attraction in pennsylvania many rangers consider it only 
an entrylevel job unlike in many other big organizations the 
staff yearns for transfers out of the big city to the boondocks 
the kind of person who wants to work for the national park 
service doesnt exactly envision working in downtown 
philadelphia pollarine says after a year here many of them 
are looking for someplace else to work 
rangers are just like other people says ranger steve 
perlman when they think of the national parks they think of 
yellowstone 
besides hearing the call of the wild park rangers here have to 
deal with the cost of living in the city a starting park rangers 
salary is about 17000 a year 
while many park service trainees come out of college an 
increasing number are retired from teaching or military service 
a lot of people you meet here are academically very well 
trained pollarine says 
philadelphia ranks as a good place for rangers to prove 
themselves on busy days tours are given every 15 minutes at 
independence hall with 85 people going through the building at a 
time dutcher says 
on the average day we get about 2000 to 3000 people says 
ranger bill kashatus on peak days in may its not unusual for 
8000 schoolchildren to visit the liberty bell 
the training continues after the rangers go on duty every other 
week the park has a 45minute session focusing on a special topic 
because the bill of rights will be a hot topic in 1991 its 
bicentennial year the rangers will soon hear a speaker on james 
madison who drafted the documents 
we never feel that we have all the information that we need 
mcclennie says its a neverending course of study 
the rewards may not be tangible but they are here 
not to be corny about it but this is a very special place 
pollarine says its very important to a lot of people ive seen 
people cry during tours 
</TEXT>
