<TEXT>
investigators and auditors in the agriculture 
department are sniffing at commodity programs farm loans and 
dozens of other nuts and bolts that federal workers operate jiggle 
and shift into gear 
the specialists work for the departments office of inspector 
general auditors check on whether money is spent properly and 
investigators look for ways to put people in jail if it isnt 
inspector general leon snead says in his agencys annual plan 
for the fiscal year that began oct 1 that auditors identified 
about 328 million in recoveries and collections last year 
further he said usda managers committed themselves to putting 
4201 million to better use 
investigations resulted in 839 indictments 671 convictions and 
about 388 million in fines restitutions and recoveries during 
the year 
what about 1991 more of the same with auditors looking into 
consumer protection programs such as meat and poultry large 
payments to farmers export credit operations and financial 
management 
snead said his office also will monitor implementation of 
the 1990 farm law this year and will conduct a financial statement 
audit of the farmers home administration 
our investigative priorities include the timely and thorough 
investigation of threats to the health and safety of the public 
employee integrity issues and fraud in the loan regulatory and 
benefit program he said 
the 75page annual report was made available to the associated 
press upon request 
according to the audit blueprint for 1991 there will be further 
looks into operations of various programs operated by the 
departments agricultural stabilization and conservation service 
and its national network of state and county offices 
in fiscal year 1990 we continued to find problems with 
excessive deficiency payments subsidies to producers deliberate 
circumvention of the payment limitation provisions payments for 
ineligible cropland in the conservation reserve program and 
incorrect crop yields and payment rates used to calculate disaster 
payments the report said 
previous audits it added also identified weaknesses in 
producer payment certifications compliance with costsharing 
agreements and other details of the commodity programs 
among the audits of ascs planned for fiscal 1991 are major 
audits of compliance with payment limitation provisions the 1989 
disaster assistance program tobacco program operations claims and 
debt management activities and the 1990 emergency feed program 
the report said 
on the investigative side the report said a significant 
number of staff days will be spent in several areas 
investigation of farmers who have used a scheme or device 
to avoid annual crop support payment limitations 
the investigation of false certification by farmers so they 
could get disaster assistance 
investigation of shortages of usdaowned or usdamortgaged 
commodities stored in commercial warehouses 
the report said auditors will review marketing opportunities 
provided by the support for eastern european democracy act of 1989 
compliance with international trade agreements a followthrough on 
prior recommendations for export subsidy programs and 
implementation of new trade provisions of the 1990 farm law 
on the investigative side the report said this years efforts 
will be increased to 3 percent of the offices total staff days 
from 25 percent last year and 05 percent in 1988 
most of the investigations involved the public law 480 food 
for peace program the export enhancement program and the export 
credit guarantee program usually involving allegations of false 
certifications by us exporters 
