<TEXT>
love is a strange hotel rna gregson and collister 
 
one problem with people who use acoustic guitars as a primary 
means of musical expression is inflation of their songs and 
themselves 
such selfimportance causes folkrock artists clive gregson and 
christine collister to miss a good opportunity with their new disc 
love is a strange hotel on the record the duo abandon their 
own relatively undistinguished compositions for an eclectic set of 
cover songs 
their choices show a wideranging taste unfortunately a few 
bad song choices and overwrought performances make this an overall 
disappointment 
when aztec cameras roddy frame sings his own how men are 
it works as a man extending an arm in sympathy to a woman whos 
been jilted switch the sex of the narrator and collister turns the 
song into selfpitying malebashing 
similarly turning 10ccs the things we do for love and paul 
carracks always better with you into acoustic ballads comes 
off as a misguided attempt to turn pop into poetry carracks song 
is a soulful shout of joy and needs more exuberance than gregson 
and collister can give it 
the performances of bruce springsteens one step up and 
jackson brownes for a dancer bring emotional ballads one step 
closer to new age background music 
collister has one shining moment that almost cancels out her 
sins elsewhere the pain in her voice perfectly captures the 
heartache of unrequited love on stephen fearings the most 
beguiling eyes merle haggards today i started loving you 
again gives the pair its most effective duet 
