<TEXT>
a woman slumped in a phone booth crying a 
cheap motel the rotting door of an outdoor toilet 
this is carver country raymond carver country stories and 
poems set in the pacific northwest that make twin peaks seem as 
threatening as honey i shrunk the kids couples drink and 
fight a man grovels at the knees of his exwife furniture is sold 
on the front lawn 
a little autobiography and a lot of imagination are best 
carver once wrote these bleak images were based on real places and 
real people he grew up working class in yakima wash and wrote 
about it even when he could afford to live elsewhere he was a 
longtime drunk who later composed toughlove stories 
carver country scribners 35 collects photographs of the 
late writers friends and family and of yakima and other places he 
lived the pictures fittingly are in black and white some of 
them are pretty shots of water and open fields but the majority 
show seedy bars rundown buildings and faces that stare instead of 
smile 
he was from the start an imagemaker carvers wife 
authorpoet tess gallagher recalled in a interview that would 
correspond to writing photographically he would zero in on some 
precise detail 
color doesnt render ideas very well photographer bob 
adelman insisted during a phone interview i think of the broken 
door in this motel ray sent me to god knows what it would look 
like in color or the broken saws in the factory his father worked 
theyre strong images of things not working out 
in 1984 life magazine thought the author might win the pulitzer 
prize and assigned adelman to spend a couple of months with him 
william kennedy won but adelman came up with another project 
combine pictures of carver and the people and places he had known 
with the writing they helped inspire carver died of cancer at age 
50 in 1988 but adelman continued taking several photographs last 
year 
because rays descriptions were often minimal it was a great 
opportunity for photographs adelman said most of the pictures 
were based on real things in his stories you kind of learned what 
he was familiar with and where his imagination took off from 
gallagher who contributes an introduction to the book didnt 
like the title at first it seemed smug condescending a way of 
taking a vast and complex body of work and reducing it to a catch 
phrase 
but she warmed to it like the best of carvers stories it was 
simple but not simplistic carver country is a place but its 
also a state of mind a sense of holding on against bad luck a 
resignation to living with debts that no one could possibly expect 
to pay 
his earlier stories were the strong silent type flat on the 
surface full of mystery and terror underneath 
in why honey a woman is surprised to learn her son a 
good boy set off firecrackers in a girls ears the eerie so 
much water so close to home tells of a man who finds a 
mutiliated body in the river and takes his time letting anybody 
know what happened 
carver wasnt trying to write who killed laura palmer 
thrillers mysteries remained mysteries important questions were 
left unanswered perhaps because the author himself didnt know how 
to resolve them 
i met him at this writers conference in dallas in the 1977 
gallagher recalled i had gone home with his books and i was 
reading aloud one of the stories to my sister she said i dont 
know what happens at the end of that story call him up 
so i decided id call him up i called him up and said were 
not satisfied with this story what is going on here he said 
im not going to tell you any more 
but carver changed his luck changed he had nearly died from 
alcohol in the mid1970s he was suffering from blackouts and 
depression and was hospitalized several times living alone his 
first marriage destroyed carver joined alcoholics anonymous in 
1977 and finally stopped drinking 
gratified just to be writing again he was eager to fill in the 
blanks cathedral his acclaimed collection of stories was 
published in 1984 and people started talking 
in where im callng from two recovering alcoholics comfort 
each other on the front porch of a dryingout facility in the 
title story two men one of them blind sketch a cathedral 
together his fingers rode my fingers as my hand went over the 
paper the man who sees explains it was like nothing else in 
my life up to now 
a small good thing was the peak the story of a young 
couples heartbreaking trip through carver country and the lonely 
baker who gives them hope for a way out gallagher received a 
letter from a woman who had read it on a plane and burst out 
crying 
with the success of cathedral carver returned to his first 
love poetry he was living with gallagher and writing more 
beautifully than ever but his health broke down by 1988 he had 
developed tumors in his brain and in his lungs he died that 
august 
dont weep for me carver wrote in gravy one of his 
last poems ive had 10 years longer than i or anyone expected 
pure gravy and dont forget it 
all of us who knew ray are still bumping into walls trying to 
get on with our lives said gallagher who had married carver in 
his last june 
the feeling has been if you have tough times tough luck 
she said if things are rough you must have deserved it you 
didnt work hard enough he made the educated segment aware that 
these people had feelings and the dimensions of their suffering 
became real and palpable 
