<TEXT>
it took the closing of an oklahoma 
foundry to get singer joe diffie into the country music business 
he had long dreamed of having a career in music and when he was 
laid off in 1986 he decided to move to nashville and pursue one 
the twist of fate paid off diffies first record home was 
a no 1 hit in november 
seeing it come to fruition is very gratifying the 
31yearold performer said in an interview during his third day 
back in nashville after a whirlwind fiveweek tour of 
onenighters 
diffie had been working at the foundry in duncan okla running 
a core machine when he lost his job and his 1700amonth salary 
i never had any hair left on my arms it was always singed 
off he recalled about the job i always had burns all over me 
i detested every second of the job i didnt like any aspect of it 
except the people there 
it was a blessing in disguise when it shut down if it hadnt 
id probably still be there or some place like it 
after reaching nashville he took a job for 1 years in the 
shipping and receiving department at the gibson guitar factory 
home spent six weeks in the top 10 on the country music 
popularity charts faring better than tunes by more established 
singers such as anne murray and eddie rabbitt 
the wistful song is about the values of home life 
a swimming hole and fishing pole and the feel of the muddy 
road between my toes 
a back yard swing where i wuld sit and mom would sing 
amazing grace while she hung out the clothes 
an easy chair with my daddy there and the smell of sunday 
supper on the stove 
diffie said the song stirred strong emotions 
i think everybody related to it regardless of whether they 
were raised in the country or city because everybody has a home in 
their memory when i first heard it i got a lump in my throat it 
brings back a feeling of when you were younger safe and secure 
without any worries and no problems 
it was a sweet song but not too syrupy 
the tune is on his first album a thousand winding roads on 
epic records the lp is a mixture of ballads and uptempo songs 
performed in a style described by billboard magazine as randy 
travis with a merle haggard catch to his voice 
his second single released from the album is if you want me 
to a traditional country weeper about a man offering to leave 
his lover if thats what she wants 
another cut on the lp there goes the neighborhood is a 
ballad about marriages dissolving the cut almost home is about 
the decline of an aging parent 
diffie who cowrote four of the songs on the album says hes 
taken advantage of a new era in country music 
theres been a changing of the guard in country music the 
listeners the artists the radio stations and the people producing 
the records he said 
the songs are getting better and better with the new 
songwriters coming in thats not to say the old ones are bad but 
its almost like country music has got a little edge to it now 
some of the more sensitive matters are being touched upon 
diffie is a native of the duncan area and spent much of his life 
there his father had a huge collection of country music and his 
parents instilled in him a love of the music he remembers singing 
amazing grace you are my sunshine and peace in the 
valley with his two sisters while they traveled in the family 
pickup truck 
he briefly attended cameron university in oklahoma and eyed a 
career as a heart surgeon or chiropractor but he was more 
interested in music 
he has a sixpiece band and a fan club with the catchy name 
diffie cult keeping things in the family his mother is its 
president 
