<DOCNO> AP901231-0206 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a new front in singapores war on smoking opens 
new years day when dutyfree cigarettes will no longer be sold to 
passengers arriving at the airport 
covering foreign visitors as well as citizens the ban is part 
of a campaign to make this island of 27 million people a nation of 
nonsmokers 
it is also part of a growing drive in asia against tobacco 
companies which have been accused of targeting women and children 
some us tobacco companies facing declining domestic sales have 
stepped up efforts to increase exports to the region 
no breakdown was available on cigarette sales to passengers 
arriving at changi airport since the same outlets also serve 
passengers changing flights dutyfree cigarettes sold aboard 
incoming aircraft are not affected nor those bought by passengers 
bound for overseas 
as a blow against tobacco the ban is not as sweeping as many 
past moves in singapore which already has the regions toughest 
controls 
smoking already is barred in restaurants supermarkets 
department stores museums pool halls public bathrooms 
libraries indoor sports arenas and other public halls cinemas 
fastfood outlets taxis buses subways government offices 
hospitals and clinics violators face a 289 fine 
smoking is is frowned upon but not yet against the law in 
private offices and clubs 
smokers may light up in bars but only during hours in which no 
food is served 
singapore airlines which barred smoking on short flights in 
1988 extended the ban in october to all regional flights of four 
hours or less 
tobacco advertising has been prohibited in singapore media since 
1970 another law last new years day barred the display of 
pointofsale ads for cigarettes in stores 
cigarette names and trademarks also are banned from motor 
vehicles souvenirs and gifts free cigarette samples are illegal 
and tobacco products cannot be given as prizes in lotteries or 
other contests 
manufacturers must rotate four different health warnings on 
their packs quarterly smoking causes heart disease smoking 
causes cancer smoking damages your lungs and smoking harms 
those around us 
the most important strategy against lung cancer is avoidance 
of smoking health minister yeo cheow tong said recently in 
announcing the dutyfree sales curb 
the lung cancer incidence rate increased from 18 cases per 
100000 people in 1972 to about 30 per 100000 in 1987 he said 
smokers are believed to comprise only 136 percent of the 
population age 15 and above but health experts were dismayed to 
discover an increase recently in the number of smokers between ages 
15 and 19 
tobacco companies joined the campaign this year to discourage 
youngsters from smoking 
we are not here to promote smoking to children but to provide 
the choice to adults who want to smoke said richard png 
executive director of the tobacco manufacturers and importers 
association 
posters bearing the message children dont smoke were 
distributed to 8000 retail outlets 
other nations in the region also have cracked down on smoking 
indonesia last month banned smoking in primary and secondary 
schools hong kong stopped televised cigarette ads dec 1 hong 
kongs legislature has urged the government to ban children under 
the age of 15 from smoking in restaurants 
malaysian airlines philippine airlines and pakistan 
international airlines forbid smoking on domestic flights 
the world health organization says nine of the 10 countries 
where smoking is most widespread are in the asiapacific region it 
warned that more women and young people are lighting up in this 
area despite the spread of lung cancer and other tobaccorelated 
diseases 
papua new guinea where 85 percent of men and 80 percent of 
women smoke tops the who list the others are fiji nepal the 
philippines indonesia bangladesh south korea japan and china 
</TEXT>
