<TEXT>
military costs in the persian gulf 
crisis have outrun saudi arabias extra revenue derived from higher 
petroleum prices and production the government said monday 
the kingdom said it was delaying promulgation of its 1991 budget 
because the uncertainty created by the crisis has made it difficult 
to project how much revenue it will get from oil 
the worlds largest oil exporter said the financial burdens it 
had to bear because of the emergency circumstances create by 
iraqs aug 2 invasion of neighboring kuwait were much more 
than the extra oil revenues 
under the 1990 budget which took effect last dec 31 the 
government revenues were forecast at 118 billion riyals or about 
314 billion expenditures were set at 143 billion riyals or 376 
billion 
the difference of 25 billion riyals was to be covered through 
issuing government development bonds 
in a statement to the official saudi press agency information 
minister ali alshaer said iraqs flagrant aggression on kuwait 
and the threats it posed to saudi territories have led the 
government to reinforce its military and upgrade services and 
public utilities 
the presence of sisterly and friendly forces has also entailed 
extra spending on the services and infrastructure needed by these 
forces shaer said 
the statement said the rise of oil prices which have increased 
to the 2830 a barrel range from less than 22 prior to the 
crisis have helped the governments added expenses during part of 
october oil briefly surpassed the 40 a barrel level 
however the increase in expenditures for the saudis due to the 
gulf crisis was much more than the increase in petroleum 
revenues said shaer without giving further details 
the statement said it was difficult to assess anticipated 
revenues because of the unpredictability of circumstances that will 
decide the level of production and prices during the next 12 
months 
the united nations has set a jan 15 deadline for iraq to 
withdraw from kuwait 
saudi oil production has risen to around 8 million barrels a 
day from around 54 million barrels a day earlier in the year 
but saudi leader king fahd noted recently that his grade of oil 
never hit the 40abarrel figure in the first two months of the 
invasion which was for activelytraded us and north sea grades 
of oil 
he said his best grades never exceeded 26 a barrel and his 
