<TEXT>
instability in europe the threat of war in the 
middle east and economic woes everywhere pushed world stock markets 
down sharply in 1990 and strategists said the new year hinges on 
the course of those events 
in major markets japan tumbled on overvalued stocks and high 
interest rates and germany sank as the effect of abosorbing its 
formerly communist eastern neighbor set in while britain benefited 
from a weak dollar 
according to an index of 20 major markets by morgan stanley 
capital international world stock markets tumbled 23 percent in 
1990 through friday as measured in local currencies the us 
canadian and british stock markets were open monday but most 1990 
trading worldwide ended friday 
excluding the united states and canada the decline for us 
investors playing foreign markets translated to 244 percent in 
1990 compared to a 91 percent increase in dollar terms in 1989 
morgan stanley said 
bascially we had a year where the consequences of high real 
interest rates came out said richard b hoey chief economist 
with barclays de zoete wedd he said higher rates in germany and 
japan were felt worldwide 
market strategists said monday that the world developments that 
shaped 1990 will spill over as the dominant themes of 1991 among 
the key questions 
will the united states go to war with iraq rising oil prices 
had a bad inflationary effect on equity markets from stockholm to 
singapore and trading closely followed the movements of oil 
prices 
how bad will the world financial crisis get the pace of 
slowdowns in europe and japan and recessions in the britain and the 
united states and the movement of interest rates particularly in 
germany are considered keys to stock market performance in 1991 
will the tinder box politics of the soviet union ignite will 
eastern europe become more than an economic drain for the west 
economists said the potential for quick gains there is slim but 
that disaster could depress stock markets 
in the morgan stanley index japans stock market dropped 399 
percent in yen terms in 1990 the worlds second worst performance 
behind a 402 percent fall in finland germany declined 209 
percent france fell 252 percent and italy lost 29 percent in 
their local currencies 
the declines were smaller when measured in us dollars which 
fell against european currencies for the year 
the best performer in local terms was the hong kong market 
which rose 46 percent the austrian market lost just 69 percent 
in local currency and rose 49 percent in dollar terms britain 
dropped 107 percent in pounds and rose 61 percent in dollars the 
us market was down 59 percent according to morgan stanley 
in japan the nikkei index of 225 leading stocks plunged from a 
record high of 3891587 at the end of 1989 to below 20000 after 
iraqs invasion of kuwait in august the index recovered somewhat 
to end the year at 2384871 
a sharp rise in japanese interest rates helped depress equity 
investment there hoey said that combined with what was widely 
considered an unsustainable market level spurred the selloff 
major factors in 1991 are the real estate prices and whether 
economic malaise will increase 
interest rates played the primary role in germany with the 
powerful bundesbank the nations central bank dictating action in 
other european capitals 
the frankfurt stock market soared in the spring amid optimism 
over eastern europe before the cost of german reunification took 
its toll the german government hiked interest rates to offset the 
inflationary impact of pouring billions of dollars into former east 
germany 
higher interest rates dampen corporate expansion and economic 
growth generally 
its almost as if they flew an airplane over east germany and 
threw deutsche marks out the window hoey said the consequence 
was a widening budget deficit increased financing pressure and the 
antiinflationary response of the bundesbank 
smaller foreign markets were affected by the interest rate rise 
the netherlands stock market for instance lost 174 percent in 
1990 in local terms according to morgan stanley the us 
recession also damped enthusiasm for investing in companies that do 
business in the united states 
the dutch have a saying when it rains outside holland they 
too sometimes get a little wet said palmer davidsen who watches 
the dutch market for abnamro securities new york a subsidiary of 
a dutch bank 
people are starting to think twice about buying stocks that 
have big dollar exposure or big economic exposure in the united 
states she said 
also the widely hopedfor benefits of investment in the 
emerging democracies of eastern europe didnt materialize for 
european companies analysts said they said improvements there 
could help european markets but warned that political instability 
in the soviet union could trigger a world financial crisis 
